        "description": {
            "name": "description",
            "type": "java.lang.String",
            "value": "$locale argugment of both Zend_Translate_Adapter->addTranslation and  of Zend_Translate->__construct() is not taken into account when using Zend_Translate_Adapter_Xliff.\n\nBoth of these functions call *Zend_Translate_Adapter_Xliff->_loadTranslationData() where $locale argument is simply not used!*\n{color:red}Consequence: xliff file content is not loaded correctly.{color}\n\nI've made a very simple example to illustrate this:\n1. Let's say you have the following xliff file (used to translate \"voiture\" (i.e. a car, in French) into English (thus into \"car\") called \"translation_en.xlf\":\n{noformat}<?xml version=\"1.0\" encoding=\"utf-8\"?>\n<xliff xmlns=\"urn:oasis:names:tc:xliff:document:1.1\" version=\"1.1\">\n  <file original=\"\/translation.po\" source-language=\"fr\" datatype=\"po\">\n    <body>\n      <trans-unit id=\"1\" xml:space=\"preserve\" approved=\"yes\">\n        <source>voiture<\/source>\n        <target>car<\/target>\n      <\/trans-unit>\n    <\/body>\n  <\/file>\n<\/xliff>{noformat}\n\n2. Now you have the following script which simply load xliff content:\n{noformat}<?php\nrequire_once 'Zend\/Translate.php';\n$translate = new Zend_Translate('xliff', '\/var\/www\/zend_bug\/translation_en.xlf', 'en');\n$translate->_(1);{noformat}\n\n3. To show that content is not loaded correctly, I've modified Zend_Translate_Adapter->translate(), adding \"{{die(var_dump($this->_translate));}}\" to die revealing loaded translated content\n\nIf you execute above php script, you get the following output:\n{noformat}\narray(3) {\n  [\"en\"]=>\n  array(0) {\n  }\n  [\"fr\"]=>\n  array(1) {\n    [\"voiture\"]=>\n    string(7) \"voiture\"\n  }\n  [\"\"]=>\n  array(0) {\n  }\n}\n{noformat}\n\nWhen you expect:\n{noformat}\narray(2) {\n  [\"en\"]=>\n  array(1) {\n    [\"voiture\"]=>\n    string(3) \"car\"\n  }\n  [\"fr\"]=>\n  array(1) {\n    [\"voiture\"]=>\n    string(7) \"voiture\"\n  }\n}\n{noformat}\n\nThis is linked to what I reported on bug http:\/\/framework.zend.com\/issues\/browse\/ZF-4084, i.e. Zend_Translate_Adapter_Xliff expect < file > node to have a \"target-language\" attribute, but it's optional! => if you don't specify it, $this->_target = $attrib['target-language'] is empty, generating an empty key for _translate array, even if you explicitly specified a target language when loading xliff content (i.e. when create Zend_Translate instance or when calling Zend_Translate->addTranslation() method).\n\nTo solve this bug (and get expected output), I've updated the solution I proposed on ZF-4084:\n1. I've made $locale argument of Zend_Translate_Adapter_Xliff->_loadTranslationData() useful, adding the following line in this method: \n{noformat}$this->_target = $locale;{noformat}\n2. I've updated Zend_Translate_Adapter_Xliff->_startElement() to default to $this->_target value when target-language is not specified within xliff file, replacing old content with new content:\n[old]\n{noformat}$this->_target = $attrib['target-language'];{noformat}\n[new]\n{noformat}$this->_target = array_key_exists('target-language', $attrib) ? $attrib['target-language'] : $this->_target;{noformat}\n\nWith these changes, if you re-run the script, xliff content is correctly loaded and specified $locale when loading the file is used as default target-language when none is specified within xliff file (if not specified when calling the function, may be we could try to guess it based on filename as done elsewhere).\n\nI hope I am clear enough, I've tried to do the best I could. If it's not enough, do not hesitate to contact me.\n\nRegards,\nRemy"
        },
